      "question": "For the system of equations $\\frac{2}{x} + \\frac{3}{y} = 13$ and $\\frac{5}{x} - \\frac{4}{y} = -2$, where $x, y \\neq 0$, find the value of $x + y$.",
      "answer": "$1$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Substitute $u = \\frac{1}{x}$ and $v = \\frac{1}{y}$ to reduce the system to linear equations: $2u + 3v = 13$ and $5u - 4v = -2$.",
          "Solve the linear system by multiplying the first by $4$ and the second by $3$: $8u + 12v = 52$ and $15u - 12v = -6$. Adding these gives $23u = 46$, so $u = 2$.",
          "Substitute $u = 2$ into $2u + 3v = 13$ to get $4 + 3v = 13$, which gives $3v = 9$, so $v = 3$.",
          "Find $x = \\frac{1}{u} = \\frac{1}{2}$ and $y = \\frac{1}{v} = \\frac{1}{3}$. Calculate $x + y = \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{3} = \\frac{5}{6}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$2u + 3v = 13 \\quad (1) \\\\ 5u - 4v = -2 \\quad (2) \\\\ (1) \\times 4 \\Rightarrow 8u + 12v = 52 \\\\ (2) \\times 3 \\Rightarrow 15u - 12v = -6 \\\\ 23u = 46 \\Rightarrow u = 2 \\\\ 2(2) + 3v = 13 \\Rightarrow 3v = 9 \\Rightarrow v = 3 \\\\ x = \\frac{1}{2}, y = \\frac{1}{3} \\\\ x + y = \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{3} = \\frac{5}{6}$"
      },
